Ninth Avenue, at Gansevoort Street, showing the curve in the first "El" line at this point. Emerging out of Greenwich Street, it continues northward to 29th Street. The view in this instance is southwestward silhouetting the steel framework against the limited west frontage lying between Gansevoort and Little West 12th Street. The last thoroughfare is on the right. Note the flag poles at the corners of same. For additional views of this early phase of the Charles C. Harvey line, see Ninth Avenue at 29th Street, and Greenwich Street at Dey Street.

1867-8

Gift of Major Quinn

Ninth Avenue, at Gansevoort Street, showing the "El" curve at this point after its emergence out of Greenwich Street. The photographer is viewing southward from a point slightly above Little West 12th Street. The latter appears at the right. Note the drum like apparatus required to continue the wire cable. This method of locomotion was replaced with small steam locomotives.

1867-8

Gift of Major Quinn

46-56 Gansevoort Street, at, adjoining and west of the S.W. corner of Greenwich Street, as seen from under the Ninth Ave. Elevated. On the right is shown No. 3 Ninth Ave., at the N.W. corner of Gansevoort Street.

July 7, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

The New York Times of July 9, 1938 reports that the corner buildings numbered 46-50 Gansevoort Street and 842-6 Greenwich Street, forming a plot 92.9 x 69.2 will be improved with a one and two story structure for offices and storage by the owner, the Spanish-American Mercantile Co. Inc. at a cost of $27,000; Charles H. Stadler, Engineer.

Gansevoort Street (formerly Great Kills Road), east from the S.E. corner at the northern end of Greenwich Street, showing the eastern end of Little West 12th Street (a bit of the true West 12th Street) at the left. The photographer is standing under the Ninth Avenue Elevated.

April 20, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

Frame shed between 51 and 53 Gansevoort Street, adjoining the N.W. corner at the lower end of Ninth Avenue.
April 26, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

53-61 Gansevoort Street, north side, west of Ninth Avenue. A Ninth Avenue street car is traveling east on Gansevoort Street.
April 20, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.

Gansevoort Street, north side, from the southern end of Ninth Avenue to Washington Street. The little three-story building at No. 69 is a frame house.

April 20, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

848 to 834 Greenwich Street, west side, south from Gansevoort (right) to but not including Horatio Streets, as seen across the clearance at the S.E. corner.

April 17, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Greenwich Street, south from Gansevoort Street. The street car tracks are being removed by the W.P.A. Overhead is the Ninth Avenue Elevated Line. This is shortly to be removed. At the right are No's. 838 & 842 Greenwich Street. The present Phillips Building replaced the former, and a new two story taxpayer the latter. The highstoop houses beyond are still standing. This data personally observed on 9-26-1940.

W. P. A. photo
Five Boroughs Project

June 2, 1937

Gansevoort Street, south side, west from Greenwich Street (9th Avenue elevated line thereon) showing a portion of the wholesale produce market that is located in this area. To the left are buildings on the west side of Greenwich Street extending south from Gansevoort to Horatio Streets. The empty lot seen in the foreground is at the S.E. corner of this point.
No. 2 and 3 show only the Gansevoort Street buildings. On the right of the former is the Manhattan Refrigerating Co. plant on Washington Street.
